# find variables that are in both files
compare_dfs <- function( df1, df2 )
{
  # use regular expressions to remove numeric suffixes 
  var.names.1 <- names( df1 )
  var.names.1 <- gsub( "[.][xy]$", "", var.names.1 )
  var.names.1 <- gsub( "[0-9]{2}$", "", var.names.1 )
  
  var.names.2 <- names( df2 )
  var.names.2 <- gsub( "[.][xy]$", "", var.names.2 )
  var.names.2 <- gsub( "[0-9]{2}$", "", var.names.2 )
  
  shared <- intersect( var.names.1, var.names.2 ) %>% sort()
  print( "SHARED VARIABLES:")
  print( shared )
  
  not.shared <- c( setdiff( var.names.1, var.names.2 ),
                   setdiff( var.names.2, var.names.1 ) ) %>% sort()
  
  print( "NOT SHARED:" )
  print( not.shared )
  
  d.vars1 <- data.frame( type="shared", variables=shared, stringsAsFactors=F )
  d.vars2 <- data.frame( type="not shared", variables=not.shared, stringsAsFactors=F )
  dd <- rbind( d.vars1, d.vars2 )
  
  return( dd )
}

Part 4 Results

Each of the three variables I chose (percent white residents, percent with college or greater education level, and poverty rate) did significantly predict change in median home values from 2000 to 2010. Controlling for metro area fixed effects, the amount of variance accounted for was approximately equal whether looking at any of these variables alone or in a model including two or three variableeach of these models had an Adjusted R2 of 0.29 to 0.31. This is likely because of the strong correlations between the variables.

Model 4 with all three variables included produced an Adjusted R2 of 0.31, significant at the p<0.01 level. Each of these variables had a negative correlation, thus a higher percentage of white residents, higher percentage with a college education, or higher poverty rate all indicate a smaller change in median home values.

I expected to see these relationships for percent of white and college-educated residents, since tracts with these demographics may already be high-priced and not eligible for gentrification (and I also expect the converse, that areas with low white and college-educated populations may be ripe for gentrification). However, I am surprised to see that poverty rate is also a negative correlation. This may be due to multicollinearity, since college education and poverty rate are closely correlated. In Model 2 where college education is not included, poverty rate has a positive correlation with median home value change.
